{
  "text": "Although the precise molecular mechanisms are still the subject of controversy, several lines of evidence suggest a close relationship between diabetes mellitus (DM) and many tumors including those of the pancreas, liver, and breast [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Recent studies have provided substantial evidence that DM may contribute to the pathogenesis of cSCC. Primary cSCC presenting as chronic diabetic foot ulcers has been proposed as a complication of DM [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . More recently, a elaborate study demonstrated that oral SCC in DM patients was associated with poorer prognoses compared to oral SCC in non-DM patients [CITATION_8] . Furthermore, oral administration of metformin, a traditional anti-DM drug, can significantly improve the overall survival of DM patients with head and neck cSCC [CITATION_9] . In this study, we report the first case of cutaneous SCC with clear cell/signet-ring cell morphology found in the right thigh of a woman with type 2 DM. Immunohistochemistry and HPV typesepcific PCR and genotyping were employed to explore the possibly underlying mechanisms.",
